          "prompt_html": "<h1>NOTE COMPLETION 15</h1><p><strong>Questions 31 - 40</strong></p><p>Complete the notes.</p><p>Use <strong>NO MORE THAN THREE WORDS AND / OR A NUMBER</strong> for each answer.</p><p><strong>THE MEGALODON</strong> (<em>Carcharodon Megalodon</em>) - the largest predator that ever lived on Earth</p><p>Description</p><table><thead><tr><th><strong>Size</strong></th><th>12 m + (possibly up to 15 m or 31 m)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td></td><td>About 3 x length of Great White Shark (estimates from fossilised teeth and vertebrae).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Teeth</strong></td><td>Size of <blank data-qid=\"q31\"/></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Very hard and fossilised well, unlike all other parts of sharks’ cartilage skeletons.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>A material similar to bone and covered with <blank data-qid=\"q32\"/></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Like Great White Shark teeth, but bigger, thicker and more finely serrated.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Appearance</strong></td><td>Possibly like a huge, streamlined Great White Shark.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Jaws</strong></td><td>Open <blank data-qid=\"q33\"/><br>wide and 7 feet high; could swallow enormous objects.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Loosely attached by ligaments and muscles to the skull.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Teeth probably located in rotating rows.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>First two rows of teeth for <blank data-qid=\"q34\"/>; others move as necessary.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Lost, broken or worn teeth replaced by new ones.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Did not chew food; gulped whole large chunks.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Diet</strong></td><td>Mainly whales.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Sharks eat approx. <blank data-qid=\"q35\"/> of body weight daily.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Remains of whales with large <blank data-qid=\"q36\"/> from serrated teeth - indicates predator - prey relationship.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Timeline</strong></td><td>Megalodon existed in Miocene and Pliocene epochs (25 million - 1.6 million years ago).</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>The precise time of its <blank data-qid=\"q37\"/> remains moot; could be only 10,000 years ago.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Research shows that if Megalodon is extinct, it is only recently in the <blank data-qid=\"q38\"/>.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Other large animals can stay hidden, so maybe Megalodon still exists somewhere.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Sightings</strong></td><td>In 1918, Australian crayfishmen reported an enormous shark attacking their pots. They said it was huge - approximately <blank data-qid=\"q39\"/> in length. The sighting was never repeated.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Megalodon’s existence today is debated only on <blank data-qid=\"q40\"/><br>.</td></tr></tbody></table>",
